  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant penalties. Here are some key details:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 20 years\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Forfeiture of assets related to the laundering activity\n\n2. Fine Amounts:\n- Fines can be up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Potential asset seizure\n- Impact on future employment opportunities\n\n4. Specific Statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 covers money laundering criminal offenses\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 addresses monetary transactions in criminally derived property\n\n5. Aggravating Factors:\n- Penalties may increase if laundering is connected to specific crimes like drug trafficking or terrorism\n\nExact penalties can vary based on specific circumstances, transaction amounts, and whether it's a first-time or repeat offense. Consulting with a legal professional would provide the most precise guidance for a specific situation.",
